Please rephrase this Answer: ...the most common way to use an IF statement in C++ is to compare two values using the relational operators (==,!=, <, >, <=, >=) and then execute a block of code if the comparison is true. For example:

```c++
int x = 5;
int y = 10;

if (x < y) {
    std::cout << "x is less than y" << std::endl;
}
```

In the given code, the IF statement checks if the value of x is less than the value of y.

Please rephrase this Answer: ...you can set the color of the text using CSS. You can add a class to the text element and define the color in the CSS file. For example, you could have a CSS class called "red-text" and set the color property to red in the CSS file. Then, in your HTML, you can add the class to the text element to change its color. Here's an example:

```html
<p class="red-text">This text will be red.</p>
```

```css
.red-text {
  color: red;
}
``
